"Bopp L., Aumont O., Cadule P., Alvain S., Gehlen M.","Response of diatoms distribution to global warming and potential implications: A global model study",2005,"Geophysical Research Letters","32","19", L19606,"1","4",,,10.1029/2005GL023653,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-28144449712&partnerID=40&md5=c90b9cc2ff36dd5a4f6bca014a12d6d9","Laboratoire des Sciences du Climate et de l'Environnement, Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CEA/CNRS, F-91191 Gif sur Yvette, France; Laboratoire Océan Climat Exploitation et Application Numérique, Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CNRS/IRD/UPMC, BP 70, F-29280 Plouzané, France; Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CNRS, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4 place Jussieu, F-75252 Paris Cedex 5, France","Bopp, L., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climate et de l'Environnement, Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CEA/CNRS, F-91191 Gif sur Yvette, France; Aumont, O., Laboratoire Océan Climat Exploitation et Application Numérique, Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CNRS/IRD/UPMC, BP 70, F-29280 Plouzané, France; Cadule, P., Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CNRS, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4 place Jussieu, F-75252 Paris Cedex 5, France; Alvain, S., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climate et de l'Environnement, Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CEA/CNRS, F-91191 Gif sur Yvette, France; Gehlen, M., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climate et de l'Environnement, Institut Pierre-Simon Laplace, CEA/CNRS, F-91191 Gif sur Yvette, France","Using a global model of ocean biogeochemistry coupled to a climate model, we explore ihe effect of climate change on the distribution of diatoms, a key phytoplankton functional group. Our model results suggest that climate change leads to more nutrient-depleted conditions in the surface ocean and that it favors small phytoplankton at the expense of diatoms. At 4×CO2, diatoms relative abundance is reduced by more than 10% at the global scale and by up to 60% in the North Atlantic and in the subantarctic Pacific. This simulated change in the ecosystem structure impacts oceanic carbon uptake by reducing the efficiency of the biological pump, thus contributing to the positive feedback between climate change and the ocean carbon cycle. However, our model simulations do not identify this biological mechanism as a first-order process in the response of ocean carbon uptake to climate change. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atoms; Carbon; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Global warming; Marine biology; Mathematical models; Natural water geochemistry; Remote sensing; Climate model; Diatoms distribution; Ocean biogeochemistry; Ocean physics; Oceanic carbon uptake; Oceanography; diatom; global warming; modeling; Bacillariophyta",,,,,,"Alvain, S., Moulin, C., Dandonneau, Y., Bréon, F.-M., Remote sensing of phytoplankton groups in case 1 waters from global SeaWiFS imagery (2005) Deep Sea Res., (PART I). , in press; Aumont, O., Maier-Reimer, E., Blain, S., Monfray, P., An ecosystem model of the global ocean including Fe, Si, P co-limitations (2003) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 17 (2), p. 1060. , doi:10.1029/2001GB001745; Bopp, L., Monfray, P., Aumont, O., Dufresne, J.L., LeTreut, H., Madec, G., Terray, L., Orr, J., Potential impact of climate change on marine export production (2001) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 15, pp. 81-99; Bopp, L., Kohfeld, K.E., Quéré, C.L., Aumont, O., Dust impact on marine biota and atmospheric pCO2 during glacial periods (2003) Paleoceanography, 18 (2), p. 1046. , doi:10.1029/2002PA000810; Cox, P.M., Betts, R.A., Jones, C.D., Spall, S.A., Totterdell, I.J., Acceleration of global warming due to carbon-cycle feedbacks in a coupled climate model (2000) Nature, 408, pp. 184-187; Dufresne, J.-L., Fairhead, L., LeTreut, H., Berthelot, M., Bopp, L., Ciais, P., Friedlingstein, P., Monfray, P., On the magnitude of positive feedback between future climate change and the carbon cycle (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29 (10), p. 1405. , doi:10.1029/2001GL013777; Friedlingstein